thods of the numeric types and the date and time types use the current thread culture for formatting operations.","pos":[38832,39044],"source":" By default, the <xref:System.String.Format%2A?displayProperty=fullName> method and the `ToString` methods of the numeric types and the date and time types use the current thread culture for formatting operations."},{"content":"To explicitly specify that the formatting method should use the current culture, you can call an overload of a formatting method that has a <ph id=\"ph1\">`provider`</ph> parameter, such as <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.String.Format%28System.IFormatProvider%2CSystem.String%2CSystem.Object%5B%5D%29?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> or <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.DateTime.ToString%28System.IFormatProvider%29?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph>, and pass it the <ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> property.","pos":[39045,39531],"source":" To explicitly specify that the formatting method should use the current culture, you can call an overload of a formatting method that has a `provider` parameter, such as <xref:System.String.Format%28System.IFormatProvider%2CSystem.String%2CSystem.Object%5B%5D%29?displayProperty=fullName> or <xref:System.DateTime.ToString%28System.IFormatProvider%29?displayProperty=fullName>, and pass it the <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=fullName> property."},{"content":"You can persist non-string data either as binary data or as formatted data.","pos":[39538,39613]},{"content":"If you choose to save it as formatted data, you should call a formatting method overload that includes a <ph id=\"ph1\">`provider`</ph> parameter and pass it the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture%2A?displayProperty=fullName&gt;</ph> property.","pos":[39614,39850],"source":" If you choose to save it as formatted data, you should call a formatting method overload that includes a `provider` parameter and pass it the <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture%2A?displayProperty=fullName> property."},{"content":"The invariant culture provides a consistent format for formatted data that is independent of culture and machine.","pos":[39851,39964]},{"content":"In contrast, persisting data that is formatted by using cultures other than the invariant culture has a number of limitations:","pos":[39965,40091]},{"content":"The data is likely to be unusable if it is retrieved on a system that has a different culture, or if the user of the current system changes the current culture and tries to retrieve the data.","pos":[40101,40292]},{"content":"The properties of a culture on a specific computer can differ from standard values.","pos":[40302,40385]},{"content":"At any time, a user can customize culture-sensitive display settings.","pos":[40386,40455]},{"content":"Because of this, formatted data that is saved on a system may not be readable after the user customizes cultural settings.","pos":[40456,40578]},{"content":"The portability of formatted data across computers is likely to be even more limited.","pos":[40579,40664]},{"content":"International, regional, or national standards that govern the formatting of numbers or dates and times change over time, and these changes are incorporated into Windows operating system updates.","pos":[40674,40869]},{"content":"When formatting conventions change, data that was formatted by using the previous conventions may become unreadable.","pos":[40870,40986]},{"content":"The following example illustrates the limited portability that results from using culture-sensitive formatting to persist data.","pos":[40993,41120]},{"content":"The example saves an array of date and time values to a file.","pos":[41121,41182]},{"content":"These are formatted by using the conventions of the English (United States) culture.","pos":[41183,41267]},{"content":"After the application changes the current 